thou hit upon these answers thyself, or did some one else tell
thee?                     To tell the truth, they are not my own; the
lovely damsel taught me these answers.                     She has
taught thee well too, sage indeed must she be. Go to her and tell her
in my name that if she be so wise and sensible she must appear before
me to-morrow: neither on foot nor on horseback, neither naked nor
clothed, and with a [ a id="pb227" href="#pb227"
name="pb227">227]present in her hand that is no gift. If she
accomplish this I will reward her as becomes a Tsar, and make her
higher than the highest.        Again the orphan went out of the town,
and again he fell a-fretting, and he said to himself:        Why, I
don       t even know how and have no idea where to find this lovely
damsel; what sort of a task is this that I am bidden to give
her?        No sooner had he thought this than the sage and lovely
damsel again passed by that way. The orphan told her how his guesses
had pleased the Tsar, and how he wanted to see the damsel himself and
